==Inspiration==
The short story of ''Smith of Wootton Major'' was conceived by Tolkien while trying to write an introduction to a book of [[George MacDonald]]. When [[Clyde S. Kilby]] asked Tolkien if the story referred to MacDonald, he denied it, but Kilby noticed that Old Nokes could represent the opinion Tolkien had of MacDonald: the character only cares of making the children happy with old recipes and a fairy queen made of sugar, ignoring the true meaning of the star within the cake or meeting the actual Fairy Queen.<ref>[[Clyde S. Kilby]], [[Tolkien and The Silmarillion]], II. "Summer with Tolkien", pp. 36-39</ref>

